  <h>ethnonymic common nouns</h>
  <p>Ethnonymic common nouns are <a href="?xx=nouns/anthropic_common_nouns">anthropic common
      nouns</a> which characterise a person in terms of their ethno-cultural heritage
    or lineage eg. <a href="?gd=Gàidheal">Gàidheal</a>
    <masc/>
    <en>Gael, Highlander</en>, <a href="?gd=Leòdhas">Leòdhasach</a>
    <masc/>
    <en>person from Lewis</en>, <a href="?gd=Caimbeul">Caimbeulach</a>
    <masc/>
    <en>a Campbell</en>.</p>
  
  <p>Note that ethnonymic common nouns are always capitalised, and are almost always derived from <a
      href="?xx=nouns/proper_nouns">proper nouns</a> using the suffix <b><a href="?gd=_ach"
        >-(e)ach</a></b>. These nouns are always masculine, and genitives and plural are always
    formed by slenderisation.</p>
  <p>There are three main kinds of ethnonymic common nouns – <ul>
      <li><u>Demonymic</u> common nouns are derived from <a href="?xx=nouns/toponymic_proper_nouns"
          >toponymic proper nouns</a> and refer to a person who originates from the area in question
        eg. <i>Leòdhas</i>
        <en>Lewis</en> ⇒ <m>Leòdhasach</m>
        <en>person from Lewis</en>, <i>Muile</i>
        <en>Mull</en> ⇒ <m>Muileach</m>
        <en>person from Mull</en>. <boxlink ref="#demonyms"/></li>
      <li><u>Patronymic</u> common nouns are derived from <a
          href="?xx=nouns/anthroponymic_proper_nouns">anthroponymic proper nouns</a> and refer to a
        person who is descended from the person in question eg. <i>Friseal</i>
        <en>Fraser</en> ⇒ <m>Frisealach</m>
        <en>a member of the Fraser family</en>, <i>Caimbeul</i>
        <en>Campbell</en> ⇒ <m>Caimbeulach</m>
        <en>a Campbell</en>. <boxlink ref="#patronyms"/></li>
      <li>Pure ethnonyms eg. <m>Gàidheal</m>
        <en>Gael</en>, <m>Cruithneach</m>
        <en>Pict</en>, <m>Gall</m>
        <en>Lowlander</en>.</li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  <p>Note that ethnonymic common nouns are often used in <a
      href="?xx=nouns/anthroponymic_name_descriptions">anthroponymic</a> and <a
      href="?xx=nouns/ergonyms">ergonymic</a> name-descriptions, eg. <i>Am Moireach</i>
    <en>The Duke of Atholl</en>, <i>Na Caimbeulaich</i>
    <en>The Campbells</en>.</p>
  <p>Note also that the ‘femaleness’ of women described with an ethnonymic noun can be brought into
    focus with the traditional prefix <b><a href="?gd=bana">ban(a)-</a></b>, eg. <m>bana-Hearach</m>
    <en>a Harris woman</en>, <m>bana-Chaimbeulach</m>
    <en>a Campbell woman</en>.</p>

